observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
• Create a team composed of department heads to make a formal study in improving the revenue of the market and immediately act upon the various causes of losses;
• Institute actions for the intensive collection of delinquency on monthly stall fees and impose the sanctions against delinquent stallholders;
• Accept new lessees for unoccupied/vacant stalls in the market;
• Make a study for possible imposition of fees aside from business permit to the private-owned business establishments within the vicinity of the public market who are benefited by the strategic location as an additional source of income for the market operation;
• Provide justification for the awarding of more than 1 stall to a person; and implement sanctions on stall owners for violating the prohibition against sub-lease under Section 5A.08e.7 of Revised Revenue Code of 2008;
• Enjoin the Business Permit and Licensing Office and Municipal Treasurer’s Office in monitoring and exacting permit fee and other regulatory fees for businesses not only in the market but in all business establishments under its jurisdiction;
• The Municipal Mayor together with the Honorable Members of the sanggunian and the concerned officials work together for the strict implementation of the Revised Revenue Code of 2008 and for its upgraded revision.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor to instruct the concerned officials and employees to:
• ensure that the POs contain, among others, information as to the date of delivery, procurement terms and date of conforme of supplier, contact numbers and complete address of the supplier as required under COA Circular No. 96-010 dated August 15, 1996;
• strictly comply with Section 4(6) of PD 1445. Ensure that all claims against government funds be supported with all the required documentations. Require submission of lacking documents. Refrain from paying disbursement vouchers with incomplete supporting documents to avoid suspensions and disallowances in audit.

We recommended that the
Municipal Mayor:
1. Direct the Municipal Accountant and Supply Officer to: a) maintain Supplies Ledger Cards and Stock Cards, respectively, complete with all the required information; and b) reconcile their records periodically;
2. Require the inventory committee to prepare the RPCI with complete data for each item, as basis for reconciliation with the SLCs and SCs. Also, furnish the Audit Team a copy of the duly accomplished RPCI not later than January 31 of each year in accordance with the GAM for LGUs;
3. Direct the Municipal Accountant to follow the proper accounting procedures for inventories as prescribed in the GAM for LGUs; and
4. Prepare Adjusting Journal Entries to record the inventories found on hand to present fairly the Financial Statements of the Municipality.

 Creation and/or Strengthening of the LGU GAD Focal Point System (GFPS);
 Establishment and Maintenance of GAD Database;
 Gender and Development (GAD) Planning and Budgeting;
 Mainstreaming Gender Perspectives in Local Development Plans; and
 Formulation/Enhancement and Implementation of the LGU GAD Code

We recommended that the Municipality strictly and fully comply with the Section 4 of Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01 of Philippine Commission on Women, Department of the Interior and Local Government, Department of Budget and Management and National Economic and Development Authority that as a strategy to implement the Magna Carta of Women, the Local Government Unit shall pursue gender mainstreaming in its locality. As such, it shall ensure that the following mechanisms and processes are in place:
 Creation and/or Strengthening of the LGU GAD Focal Point System (GFPS);
 Establishment and Maintenance of GAD Database;
 Gender and Development (GAD) Planning and Budgeting;
 Mainstreaming Gender Perspectives in Local Development Plans; and
 Formulation/Enhancement and Implementation of the LGU GAD Code

For the foregoing deficiencies, we recommended the following:
 That the Local School Board strictly comply with the provisions of Joint Circular No. 1, series of 2017 of the Department of Education, Department of Budget and Management and Department of the Interior and Local Government in order to ensure that Special Education Fund (SEF) will be utilized for the intended purpose or according to the identified priority areas listed in the Annual Implementation Plan (AIP) culled from the DepEd-approved School Improvement Plan (SIP);
 That the Local Chief Executive, as the Head of the Local School Board, adhere strictly with the existing laws, rules and regulations in the prioritization and utilization of Special Education Fund particularly for the operation and maintenance of public schools, construction and repair of school buildings, facilities and equipment, educational research, purchase of books and periodicals and sports development as provided in Sections 100(c) and 272 of the Local Government Code of 1991 and DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 1, s. 2017 in order to ensure an effective educational development within the locality;
 Require the concerned Department of Education officials to immediately submit the above mentioned supporting documents to substantiate the transaction; and
 That the Municipal Accountant ensure that the supporting documents were complete before the processing of claims pursuant to Section 4 (6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445 to avoid suspension in audit.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor and other officials:
Strictly implement and cause the immediate and effective rehabilitation of  the  controlled  dumpsite and eventually the construction and  maintenance  of sanitary landfill  in accordance with RA 9003;
Cause the strict implementation of Municipal Ordinance No. 007 series of 2014 “An Ordinance Adopting the Prohibition of Using Plastic Bags on Dry Goods and Regulating its Utilization on Wet Goods in the Municipality of Tuy, Batangas and Prescribing Penalties Thereof;
Submit to the Audit Team the result of cost-benefit analysis and in-depth research on the pros and cons on the use of the Multi-Purpose Shredder Machine Model LMS-400-MPS amounting to ₱1,715,954.00 prior to its procurement;
Look for possible ways on how the Multi-Purpose Shredder Machine could still be utilize without incurring too much electricity bill and review the warranty provided by the supplier for possible remedies; and
Expedite and exert more efforts for the approval of the 10 year Solid Waste Management Plan and its implementation.

We recommended that the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC):

strictly comply with the provision of aforementioned COA Circular No. 2009-001 and submit  copy of perfected contracts and purchase orders within five working days upon approval together with the required supporting documents and submit the lacking/defective documentary requirements to the Auditor for review and evaluation; 

ensure completeness of bidding documents and propriety of bidding process;


invite two(2) observers to sit in its bidding proceedings;

post the result of bidding at PhilGEPS; and

adopt the Standard Forms and Standard Bidding Documents prescribed by the GPPB Procurement Manual for the procurement of infrastructure projects or civil works.

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant refrain from processing claims without complete documentation.

We recommended that the General Service Officer, BAC Chairman, Municipal Treasurer-ICO, and Municipal Accountant:

Enjoin the submission of  authority from the Office of the Secretary of Department of the Interior and Local Government  (DILG);


Submit the supporting documents required in the National Budget Circular No. 446-A for the procurement of 2nd hand Motor Vehicle for further evaluation;

Submit justifications for non-compliance with the aforementioned requirements for the procurement of second hand vehicle.  Otherwise, this would not be considered in audit;

Ensure strict compliance with the provisions of NBC Budget Circular No. 446-A; and


Stop processing claims with incomplete/deficient supporting documents.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:


submit a letter-inquiry to the Land Registration Authority on the titling of undocumented municipal lands in preparation for their titling;

instruct the concerned official/s of the Municipality to unearth the documents establishing the Municipality/s rights/ownership over its landholdings, including the unit on which the structures of the Tuy Water District are erected;  

direct the Municipal Engineer, MGSO and/or the Municipal Assessor to submit documents regarding actual use of landholdings and estimate/s on the costs regarding the survey and submission of related application titling with the requisite certification/s; 

instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to include in the annual budget the cost/s for the titling of landholdings;


direct the Municipal Accountant to record the remaining 29 parcels of land using the available assessed/market value with proper disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements (NFS), and to record the adjustment of already-recognized land to its current fair market value, with the corresponding disclosures in the NFS, to afford uniformity in the recognition of Land.
